	add("person", "{\"term\":\"person\", \"etymology\":{\"influencers\":[], \"languages\":[\"old english (ca. 450-1100)\", \"English\", \"Latin\", \"anglo-norman\"], \"text\":\"From Anglo-norman {{m|fro|parsone}}, {{m|fro|persoun}} et al. (Old French {{m|fro|persone||human being}}, French {{m|fr|personne}}), and its source Latin {{m|la|persōna||mask used by actor; role, part, character}},perhaps a loanword; compare Etruscan {{m|ett|φersu||mask|sc\u003dLatn}}. Displaced native {{m|enm|wight}} (from Old english (ca. 450-1100) {{m|ang|wiht||person, human being}}).\"}, \"definitions\":{\"list\":[{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"by suppletion\", \"priority\":1},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"An individual; usually a human being\", \"priority\":2},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"1784\u0027\u0027, William Jones, \u0027The Description and Use of a New Portable Orrery, \u0026amp;c.\u0027, [http://www.google.co.uk/books?id\u003d4SoIAAAAIAAJ\u0026amp;pg\u003dPA1\u0026amp;dq\u003dph%C3%A6nomen\", \"priority\":3},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"PPA1,M1 P\u0026lt;small\u0026gt;REFACE\u0026lt;/small\u0026gt\", \"priority\":4},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"T\u0026lt;small\u0026gt;HE\u0026lt;/small\u0026gt; favourable reception the Orrery has met with from \u0027\u0027Perſons\u0027\u0027 of the firſt diſtinction, and from Gentlemen and Ladies in general, has induced me to add to it ſeveral new improvements in order to give it a degree of Perfection; and diſtinguiſh it from others; which by Piracy, or Imitation, may be introduced to the Public\", \"priority\":5},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"title\u003d[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the passage\u003d“A very welcome, kind, useful present, that means to the parish. By the way, Hopkins, let this go no further. We don\u0027t want the tale running round that a rich \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027 has arrived. Churchill, my dear fellow, we have such greedy sharks, and wolves in lamb\u0027s clothing.\u0026amp;nbsp;[…]”\", \"priority\":6},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"A character or part, as in a play; a specific kind or manifestation of individual character, whether in real life, or in literary or dramatic representation; an assumed character\", \"priority\":7},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Francis Baco\", \"priority\":8},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"his first appearance upon the stage in his new \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027 of a sycophant or juggle\", \"priority\":9},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Jeremy Taylo\", \"priority\":10},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"No man can long put on a \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027 and act a part\", \"priority\":11},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Milto\", \"priority\":12},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"To bear rule, which was thy part / And \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027, hadst thou known thyself aright\", \"priority\":13},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"How different is the same man from himself, as he sustains the \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027 of a magistrate and that of a friend\", \"priority\":14},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Any one of the three hypostases of the Holy Trinity: the Father, Son, or Holy Spirit\", \"priority\":15},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Book of Common Prayer\", \"priority\":16},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"three \u0027\u0027persons\u0027\u0027 and one Go\", \"priority\":17},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Any sentient or socially intelligent being\", \"priority\":18},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Someone who likes or has an affinity for (a specified thing\", \"priority\":19},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Jack\u0027s always been a dog \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027, but I prefer cats.\u0027\u0026lt;!--\u0027likes\u0027, noun phrase--\u0026gt\", \"priority\":20},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"The physical body of a being seen as distinct from the mind, character, etc\", \"priority\":21},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"III.1.2.iii\", \"priority\":22},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"when the young ladies laughed at her for it, she replied, that it was not his \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027 that she did embrace and reverence, but, with a Platonic love, the divine beauty of his soul\", \"priority\":23},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"The Captain, inclining his military \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027, sat sideways to be closer and kinder\u0026amp;nbsp;[…\", \"priority\":24},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"1978\u0027\u0027, \u0027Livia\u0027, Faber \u0026amp; Faber 1992 , p. 418\", \"priority\":25},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"At first blush it seemed that what was striking about him rested on the fact that his dress was exotic, his \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027 foreign\", \"priority\":26},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Meanwhile, the dazed Sullivan, dressed like a bum with no identification on his \u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027, is arrested and put to work on a brutal Southern chain gang\", \"priority\":27},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Any individual or formal organization with standing before the courts\", \"priority\":28},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"At common law a corporation or a trust is legally a \u0027\u0027person\", \"priority\":29},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"The human genitalia; \u0027specifically\u0027, the penis\", \"priority\":30},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"1824\u0027\u0027, ([http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1824/83/pdfs/ukpga_18240083_en.pdf 5 Geo. 4. c.\u0026amp;nbsp;83], United Kingdom), section 4\", \"priority\":31},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"E]very Person wilfully, openly, lewdly, and obscenely exposing his \u0027\u0027Person\u0027\u0027 in any Street, Road, or public Highway, or in the View thereof, or in any Place of public Resort, with Intent to insult any Female\u0026amp;nbsp;... and being subsequently convicted of the Offence for which he or she shall have been so apprehended, shall be deemed a Rogue and Vagabond, within the true Intent and Meaning of this Act\u0026amp;nbsp\", \"priority\":32},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"1972\u0027\u0027, \u0027Evans v. Ewels\u0027, \u0027Weekly Law Reports\u0027, vol. 1, p. 671 at pp.\u0026amp;nbsp;674–675\", \"priority\":33},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"It seems to me that at any rate today, and indeed by 1824, the word \u0026quot;\u0027\u0027person\u0027\u0027\u0026quot; in connection with sexual matters had acquired a meaning of its own; a meaning which made it a synonym for \u0026quot;penis.\u0026quot; It may be ... that it was the forerunner of Victorian gentility which prevented people calling a penis a penis. But however that may be I am satisfied in my own mind that it has now acquired an established meaning to the effect already stated. It is I venture to say, well known amongst those who practise in the courts that the word \u0026quot;person\u0026quot; is so used over and over again. It is the familiar synonym of that part of the body, and, as one of the reasons for my decision in this case, I would use that interpretation of what was prevailing in 1824 and what has become established in the 150 years since then\", \"priority\":34},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"A linguistic category used to distinguish between the speaker of an utterance and those to whom or about whom he is speaking. See grammatical person\", \"priority\":35},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"A shoot or bud of a plant; a polyp or zooid of the compound Hydrozoa, Anthozoa, etc.; also, an individual, in the narrowest sense, among the higher animals\", \"priority\":36},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"Encyc. Brit\", \"priority\":37},{\"upperType\":\"NOUN\", \"text\":\"True corms, composed of united personae usually arise by gemmation, yet in sponges and corals occasionally by fusion of several originally distinct \u0027\u0027persons\", \"priority\":38}]}, \"synonyms\":{}}");

